Gah, I so don't think so. Uber guild websites are not that interesting, although I've appreciated the CoH discussion on FoH's...or did until they decided it was the suxor.<br>
<br>
Eq is eating itself and that is the problem with it. How do you fix that? You either get new people to play it, and use all of the content that isn't used now (and yes, you may have to retune some of that--the point about Ldon raids is completely valid--they Should be an alternative for smaller guilds, they should have always been that)--or, you say whatever, and market to the player base you have left. I do think the end game needs fixing, yes. And I think they need to work very hard on balance if they raise the level caps again...but I'm not convinced that the answer to all of our prayers is 500 aa's to get to level 70 in some brown outdoor zone with the great exp that is really just an advanced version of OT so that we can raid the &quot;ubah&quot; content. Yeah I know, you've all got 500 aa's already...that's nice for you. I would however, be alot more excited if 50 of them weren't to reduce your missed notes, and another 50 weren't for the level cap, and another 50 were ostensibly to raise your melee dps but didn't--much and...blah.<br>
<br>
I really like CoH. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccb9b><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://p201.ezboard.com/btheconcerthall.showUserPublicProfile?gid=cosmykrocker>Cosmyk Rocker</A></span><br> Posts: 394<br> <font color=#330000>(5/28/04 2:58 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://p201.ezboard.com/ftheconcerthallbackstage.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=19425.topic&index=24>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> What's old is new again...</span><hr size=1> For those of you that have been around a while, this is a lot like what went on while Anarchy Online, and Dark Age of Camelot were in beta testing, and early release.<br>
<br>
SoE all of a sudden decided that customer service was a priority during that period and actively sought in-put from the gamers. Sadly AO failed horribly, and DAoC never materialized into anything more than EverQuest-lite. Customer service went back to sleep a few months after DAoC's release as soon as SoE realized it wasn't a threat.<br>
<br>
The difference this time around is WoW is actually looking like a threat. Some well known guilds have abandoned EQ to go to WoW, and every uber-guild has felt a big loss in their player attendance. The bottom line took a big hit.<br>
<br>
WoW the game will not cause EverQuest to lose players to anything other than people getting bored. WoW customer service and commitment to providing well tested, enjoyable, and playable content is the best part of the game so far. WoW is a lot of fun on it's own, add terrific CS and it is refreshing, and pleasurable.<br>
<br>
I still find it amazing that SoE can still think hiding unfinished expansions behind un-beatable zones continues, especially with the fiascoes of Vex Thall, and the Rathe Council. Creating zones or instances that were flat out obviously not fun, and a chore to attempt was incredulous. I am astounded at the number of times SoE can still blunder with something like Uqua.<br>
<br>
As long as share holders and bankers are calling all of the shots, SoE and EQ will continue down this path.<br>
 <p>Mercuria Cestlavie <br>
If you believe everything you read, don't read.<br>
If you believe anything you see on T.V., don't watch T.V.<br>
